oncommercial','Philip Smith','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','15765024613fa01e528f2b9','2003-10-30 04:09:05','Philip Smith','2003-10-29 12:09:05',NULL,'N'),(8,0,5,12,'SANOG II ISP Workshop Materials','Philip Smith','',2003,'July','','English','','Routing','BGP','General - Network Design and Information','OSPF','attrib-noncommercial','Philip Smith','Topics covered include General Network Design and Information, Routing, BGP, and OSPF. These materials include an agenda, workshop presentations, and classroom modules.','',NULL,NULL,'Y','9642836473fa01ff7e00d9','2003-11-01 11:31:13','Philip Smith','2003-10-29 12:16:31',NULL,'N'),(14,0,15,6,'IP and networking basics','Alan Barrett','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','General - Network Design and Information','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Topics include: the protocol stack, hop by hop forwarding, IP addresses, netmasks, CIDR prefix notation, ethernet ARP, binary arithmetic.\r\n    * Students will be able to:\r\n          o recognise the ISO OSI seven-layer model\r\n          o understand the relationship between TCP/IP model and ISO model\r\n          o describe the unifying efect of the network later\r\n          o describe how IP addresses are constructed\r\n          o convert prefix into lowest/highest IP address\r\n          o identify network and broadcast addresses\r\n          o convert prefix length into netmask\r\n          o subdivide prefixes\r\n          o explain the purpose of ARP\r\no distinguish between different network types: broadcast, point-to-point, NBMA',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','5794121454004e80c2de40','2004-01-14 14:59:12','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 22:59:12',NULL,'N'),(13,0,0,8,'Implementado BGP','Jose Dominguez','http://www.walc2002.pucmm.edu.do/material/taller4/dr2-spanish.ppt',2002,'May','','Spanish','','BGP','Routing','','','attrib-noncommercial','Steven Huter','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','6426625123fa983aba318d','2003-11-06 07:12:37','Steven Huter','2003-11-05 15:12:37',NULL,'N'),(11,0,4,12,'Introduction to BGP','Philip Smith','',2003,'January','','English','','BGP','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Philip Smith','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','21387716893fa0243428a22','2003-10-30 04:34:17','Philip Smith','2003-10-29 12:34:17',NULL,'N'),(15,0,15,6,'Cisco router configuration basics','Alan Barrett','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/10-ciscocnf/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','Routing','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Topics include: RAM, NVRAM, Flash. Logging in. Running versus startup configurations, what they do, how they can be displayed, how to change them. Configuring interfaces, startup information, static routes. How to set passwords. Updating IOS, TFTPing configuration files.\r\n    * Students will be able to:\r\n          o log onto a cisco router\r\n          o perform basic commands\r\n          o show the running and stored configuration files\r\n          o make configuration changes\r\n          o add static and default routes to a cisco router\r\n          o TFTP a config file\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','7965402764004e95ca159a','2004-01-14 15:02:04','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 23:02:04',NULL,'N'),(16,0,15,6,'Network devices (primary focus: Ethernet)','Geert Jan de Groot','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/20-netdev/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','General - Network Design and Information','','','Physical network devices','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Topics include: ethernet cabling, hub, switch, bridge, router, gateway, VLANs\r\n    * Students will be able to:\r\n          o list some commonly-used media (Ethernet, FDDI, sync P-2-P, ATM, FR)\r\n          o explain the importance of correctly wiring cable pairs\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','13448694074004eac1c863f','2004-01-14 15:08:18','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 23:08:18',NULL,'N'),(17,0,15,6,'VLAN','Geert Jan de Groot','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/22-vlan/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','General - Network Design and Information','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Topics include: definition of VLANs, usage, trunking, 802.1Q packet format.\r\n    * Students will be able to:\r\n          o Tell what VLANs are\r\n          o Explain when and how to set up VLAN trunks.\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','462582274004eb795f707','2004-01-14 15:11:02','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 23:11:02',NULL,'N'),(18,0,15,6,'Wireless networks','Geert Jan de Groot and John Brown','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/doc/jbrown/html/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','Wireless and Radio','General - Network Design and Information','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','Presentation is based on a talk given by John Brown.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','12150694034004ec2f61da9','2004-01-14 15:14:03','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 23:14:03',NULL,'N'),(19,0,15,6,'Dynamic routing protocols','Abha Ahuja','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/30-ospf/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','Routing','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','*  Topics include: What they do, why we want them. Distance vector versus link state.\r\n\r\nThis topic is part of the OSPF presentation, which is the associated file.',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','1926530434004ed3c61dc2','2004-01-14 15:18:36','Administrative Account','2004-01-13 23:18:36',NULL,'N'),(20,0,15,6,'OSPF \\\"magic\\\" exercise on cisco','Abha Ahuja','',2000,'July','','English','','Routing','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','Students will remove leftover static routes, configure OSPF (without understanding how it works), see forwarding table get built by OSPF. \r\nStudents will be able to: \r\nsee the advantages of dynamic routing ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','8597060054005575cd270d','2004-01-14 22:51:42','Administrative Account','2004-01-14 06:51:42',NULL,'N'),(21,0,15,6,'OSPF theory and configuration','Abha Ahuja','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/30-ospf/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','Routing','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','Students will be able to: \r\nexplain when to use an IGP, and when not \r\nlist advantages of OSPF over RIP, EIGRP, IS/IS (fast convergence, scalability, vendor independence, equal-cost multipath, authentication, bandwidth, classless! \r\nexplain the difference between forwarding and routing (can have multiple routing databases for different protocols but only one forwarding table \r\nidentify the lowest-cost path and equal-cost path \r\ndescribe the formation of neighbour relationships \r\nlist default values for the hellointerval and the routerdeadinterval \r\nbriefly describe database flooding and recalculation and the purpose of the DR/BDR ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','140673073840055870c14da','2004-01-14 22:56:23','Administrative Account','2004-01-14 06:56:23',NULL,'N'),(22,0,15,6,'Exercises using OSPF with cisco routers','Abha Ahuja','',2000,'July','','English','','Radius','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Students will be able to:\r\n          o rebuild the classroom exercise using single area OSPF\r\n          o configure appropriate link costs, MD5 authentication, intervals; use passive-interface default\r\n          o perform simple inspection of OSPF database (neighbours, routes, DR/BDR)\r\n          o alter topology (break links) and observe altered routes\r\n          o redistribute connected and static\r\n          o originate default route\r\n          o configure loopback interfaces\r\n          o save configs to TFTP server\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','1126730645400733f4bb08e','2004-01-16 08:44:57','Administrative Account','2004-01-15 16:44:57',NULL,'N'),(23,0,15,6,'Routing simulation on paper','Alan Barrett','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/34-paperrtr/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','Routing','','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Students will be able to:\r\n          o Simulate a distance vector protocol by passing messages around on paper\r\n          o Simulate a link state protocol by passing messages around on paper\r\n          o Calculate a forwarding table based on link state information\r\n          o Observe routing protocol convergence\r\n',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','649591988400734c419df9','2004-01-16 08:48:28','Administrative Account','2004-01-15 16:48:28',NULL,'N'),(24,0,15,6,'BGP rationale','Geert Jan de Groot','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/40-need4bgp/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','BGP','Routing','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','*  Topics include: transit, peering, scaling, the need for filtering',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Y','799734858400735bb239d8','2004-01-16 08:52:29','Administrative Account','2004-01-15 16:52:29',NULL,'N'),(25,0,15,6,'BGP Introduction','Abha Ahuja','http://www.isocws.isoc.org/inet2000/t2/41-bgp/index.htm',2000,'July','','English','','BGP','Routing','','','attrib-noncommercial','Administrative Account','    *  Topics include: Why we want it. What it does.\r\n    * Students will be able to:\r\n          o Explain why you need an EGP (you want to be able to exchange traffic/ routes with other networks; cost of transit vs peering. Can\\\'t use static routes, can\\\'t use IGP)\r\n          o Define autonomous system\r\n          o Describe the key characteristics of BGP4 (point-to-point peering, TCP, incremental updates, routes + attributes, eBGP and iBGP)\r\n          o List important attributes: AS path, nexthop, localpref, MED, communities\r\n          o Describe typical path selection by length of AS path, and outline use of prepending to influence upstream path selection\r\n          o Explain the recursive lookup of nexthop attribute\r\n          o Use the list of BGP route-selection rules\r\n          o Read a table of \\\'distances\\\' for which protocol wins\r\n          o Remember that longest prefix always wins\r\n'