\r\n\r\n    * Registry/Registrar Model and EPP.\r\n          o Introduction to EPP (Extensible Provisioning Protocol)\r\n          o Operational structure used for registry-regertrar interaction\r\n    * Third party Managed DNS Services.\r\n          o Introduction to Dynamic DNS\r\n          o Managed DNS, Secondary DNS, and Recursive DNS services (UltraDNS, no-ip, etc)\r\n\r\n',2007,'June','Y','/home/isoc/public_html/data/2007/','2020-12-18 17:17:29','Administrative Account','2007-05-26 07:24:54','admin@ws.edu.isoc.org','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,13.753980,100.501442),(254,6,'AIT Lab: APNIC Internet Resource Management - Essentials','2007-06-05','2007-06-05','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/training/2007/IRME.html','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/contact_us.html','th','Bangkok','Asia/Australia/Pacific','','','English','','','','Training room, intERLab, AIT, Thailand','','info@interlab.ait.ac.th',' Course description:\r\n\r\nThe Internet resource management essentials course (IRM E) is a one-day course designed for Internet professionals. It is aimed particularly at those responsible for administering and managing Internet resources, including IP managers, senior hostmasters and network engineers. Some understanding of networking fundamentals is assumed. The course includes modules selected from both the IRM I and IRM II courses outlined above, and is tailored to meet the needs of a targeted audience.\r\n\r\nObjectives:\r\n\r\nTo assists current / prospective APNIC members and other interested parties to request internet resources (IP address, ASN, reverse DNS delegation) the easy way. And also to keep them up-to-date and familiar with the latest policies and procedures.\r\n\r\nWho should attend?\r\n\r\nTechnical personnel who are responsible for allocating and/or assigning IP addresses such as hostmaster employees of network information centers or ISPs, network planners, designers, and network engineers or other interested persons are welcome to attend the Training.\r\n\r\nCourse Duration:\r\n\r\n1 day\r\n\r\nCourse Contents:\r\n\r\nThis training covers the followings topics:\r\n\r\n    * APNIC role in the Asia Pacific\r\n    * APNIC Policies\r\n    * Whois Database\r\n    * MyAPNIC / Data privacy\r\n    * How to request IP addresses\r\n    * Reverse DNS Delegation procedures\r\n    * Autonomous System Number procedures\r\n    * Internet Routing Registry overview ',2007,'June','Y','/home/isoc/public_html/data/2007/','2020-12-18 17:17:35','Administrative Account','2007-05-26 07:06:27','admin@ws.edu.isoc.org','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,13.753980,100.501442),(255,6,'AIT Lab: IPv6 Workshop','2007-06-06','2007-06-07','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/training/2007/IPv6.html','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/contact_us.html','th','Bangkok','Asia/Australia/Pacific','','','English','','','','Training room, intERLab, AIT, Thailand','','info@interlab.ait.ac.th',' Instructor:  APNIC Trainers\r\n\r\nCourse description:\r\n\r\nThis workshop aims to provide an understanding of the IPv6 protocol structure, address architecture, IPv6 operation and technical features, transition mechanisms and their challenges. IPv6 policy and allocation criteria will also be covered, and the current IPv6 deployment status will be discussed.\r\n\r\nIn addition, IPv6 router configuration and the configuration and operation of an IPv6 network will be demonstrated.\r\n\r\nWho should attend?\r\n\r\nAnyone interested in learning about IPv6, as well of those involved in IPv6 deployment, transition and configuration will benefit from this workshop.\r\n\r\nCourse Duration:\r\n\r\n2 days\r\n\r\nCourse Contents:\r\n\r\nThis workshop covers the followings topics:\r\n\r\n    * IPv6 rationale\r\n    * IPv6 addressing\r\n    * IPv6 features\r\n    * IPv6 control plane protocols\r\n    * IPv6 routing protocols\r\n    * IPv4 to IPv6 transition mechanisms\r\n    * IPv6 to IPv6 transition scenerios\r\n    * IPv6 policy and procedures\r\n    * How to apply for IPv6 addresses\r\n    * IPv6 deployment - country reports\r\n    * IPv6 statistics\r\n    * IPv6 - the future\r\n\r\nPrerequisite:\r\n\r\nGood knowledge of IPv4 addressing, network operations as well as knowledge of DNS, Routing with both IGP and BGP. It is important that students have good prior knowledge of operations in IPv4 in order for them to attend this workshop.\r\n\r\n',2007,'June','Y','/home/isoc/public_html/data/2007/','2020-12-18 17:17:42','Administrative Account','2007-05-26 07:04:56','admin@ws.edu.isoc.org','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,13.753980,100.501442),(256,6,'AIT Lab: Anti-Spam Tutorial','2007-06-08','2007-06-08','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/training/2007/Spam.html','http://www.interlab.ait.ac.th/contact_us.html','th','Bangkok','Asia/Australia/Pacific','','','English','','','','Training room, intERLab, AIT, Thailand','','info@interlab.ait.ac.th',' Instructor:  APNIC Trainers\r\n\r\nCourse description:\r\n\r\nUnsolicited commercial email (UCE), also known as &quot;spam&quot;, is currently the most frequent complaint from users of the Internet, and is a potential threat to the effectiveness of email as a form of communication.\r\n\r\nThis tutorials will discuss the concept of spam and examine a number of tips and measures to defend against spam. Participants will also look at ways to cut down on UCE using filters, blacklists, and other anti-spam techniques, and discuss how to set up email policies to combat spam.\r\n\r\nThe tutorial will also look at a comparative study of spam laws in the Asia Pacific region.\r\n\r\nWho should attend?\r\n\r\nThis course is aimed at email adminstrators, ISPs, end users, and anyone with an interest in combating spam.\r\n\r\nCourse Duration:\r\n\r\n2 days',2007,'June','Y','/home/isoc/public_html/data/2007/','2020-12-18 17:17:48','Administrative Account','2007-05-26 07:05:36','admin@ws.edu.isoc.org','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,13.753980,100.501442),(286,12,'RIPE NCC Regional Meeting Russia','2007-10-02','2007-10-03','http://www.ripe.net/meetings/regional/mos