 the University of Lagos, Nigeria on February 20 &amp; 21, 2008. It is organized by the Panos Institute West Africa ( PIWA), part of the EuroAfrica-ICT consortium. This two-day event will draw among 70 local and West African (Ghana, Senegal, Sierra Leone) delegates representing universities, Information and Communications Technology (ICT) companies, public institutions, Non Governmental Organizations, the European Commission and international and regional organizations dealing with ICT. This workshop will be co-prepared by PIWA and its locals partners: the Centre for Information Technology and Systems of the University of Lagos and the National Centre for Technology Management - NACETEM. This event is up to be supported by the Lagos State Government as Special Guest of Honor. This awareness workshop will more specifically aim at: (1) Introducing the objectives and activities of the EuroAfrica-ICT/START initiative; (2) Meeting the most advanced local organisations; (3) Creating awareness and sharing the objectives of the European Union&#039;s Framework Programme (FP7) and the IST Programme; (4) Discussing thematic issues depending on local needs. This last goal will be a key point of this workshop. The importance of R&amp;D and ICT in West Africa will be emphasized by representatives of the Nigeria Computer Society, Centre for Information Technology and Systems ‚Äì University of Lagos, PINET informatics, DevNet Nigeria, AITI-KACE. Global constraints and opportunities, as well as the private sector and the civil society&#039;s points of view will be outlined. Stakeholders will also give more details about status and perspectives of the EU-Sub-Saharan S&amp;T/ICT cooperation through presentations of the Information Technology Industry Association of Nigeria (ITAN), the Kwame Nkrumah University of Science &amp; Technology (KNUST), the Delegation of the European Commission in Nigeria (TBC) and the Economic Commission of West African States (ECOWAS). The Seventh Framework Programme for Research and Technological Development (FP7) (ICT Theme) will be introduced to participants (including the conditions for participation, evaluation criteria and processes) in order to increase the participation of African organisations in FP7. Ongoing initiatives on e-learning, ICT for Health, ICT access will afterwards be exposed to show that valuable R&amp;D capacities and projects have been developed in African countries upon which EU-African S&amp;T partnerships can build. The workshop will end up with a lab visit to give a concrete example and learn about recent breakthrough or process developed in Nigeria in the R&amp;D on ICT field. Several breaks, debates and thematic group discussions will offer valuable networking opportunities to interested parties seeking partnerships and broadening scientific researches&#039; horizon.',2008,'February','Y','/var/www/html/data/2008/','2020-12-18 17:26:28','Administrative Account','2008-01-17 04:11:10',NULL,'N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,6.454070,3.394670),(339,450,'LINX60','2008-02-11','2008-02-12','https://www.linx.net','','gb','London','Global','','','English','','','','Goodenough College','','','This is the quarterly member meeting of the London Internet Exchange (LINX).  If you are interested in attending, presenting or sponsoring the meeting, or would like to become a member of LINX, please use the contacts page on the LINX web-site.',2008,'February','Y','/var/www/html/data/2008/','2020-12-18 17:26:34','John Souter','2008-01-21 15:11:34','john@linx.net','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,51.508530,-0.125740),(340,12,'QUESTnet2008','2008-07-08','2008-07-11','http://questnet.edu.au','','AU','Gold Coast','Asia/Australia/Pacific','','','English','','','','Crowne Plaza Royal Pines Resort','','qnet08prog@questnet.edu.au ','',2008,'July','Y','/var/www/html/data/2008/','2020-12-18 17:26:41','Philip Smith','2014-04-29 22:30:04','hervey@nsrc.org','N',NULL,'no','no',0,0,-28.000290,153.430878),(341,451,'LINX61','2008-05-19','2008-05-